(7, 1, '2016-09-16 18:39:31', '2016-09-16 22:39:31', '<article class="grid-content large-8 ng-binding"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-6" src="http://esport.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/1434307560dota2-logo-300x169.jpg" alt="1434307560dota2-logo" width="300" height="169" />\r\n\r\nThe National Collegiate e-Sports Association has decided to cancel its 2016 season for Dota 2. This decision was soley based on the lack ofregistrations and interest from the Dota 2 collegiate community. We will use the 2016 year to build connections within the Dota 2 community. We hope that in 2017 we will be able to garner enough interest to host a Dota 2 league.\r\n\r\n</article>', 'National Collegiate Dota League Canceled', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '5-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-09-16 18:39:31', '2016-09-16 22:39:31', '', 5, 'http://esport.dev/news/5-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(8, 1, '2016-05-05 18:40:39', '2016-05-05 22:40:39', 'With the 2016 National Collegiate League of Legends League (NCLL) Division II Playoffs underway, the top teams in both conferences are battling for the Division Two champion title.\r\n\r\nPlayoffs will be conducted with a single elimination tournament bracket. For both the East and West conferences, the top four teams will compete for the title of conference champion and a spot in the East versus West finals. In each conference, the bracket is built by pitting the top contender against the team in fourth place, and the second and third place teams facing each other in the conference semifinals.\r\n\r\nPlayoff spots have been awarded based on a point system, with teams earning different amounts of points based on the outcomes of normal season matches. These matches were played as a series of two games against the same opponent, and a balanced playoff bracket was created with the point leaders from the season. During the normal season, teams were awarded three points for a win (series record 2-0), one point for a tie (series record 1-1), and zero points for a loss (series record 0-2). After many weeks of scheduling and round robin matches, our League of Legends playoff teams have emerged.\r\n<h2>Western Conference</h2>\r\nFrom the West, the four teams who earned a spot in the playoffs are (in order of playoff seed) UGA eSports: Red, UMBC Gold, USC A, and Drexel Dragoons Gold. Although UGA eSports: Red has earned the top seed in the Western bracket with zero losses, UMBC Gold and USC A both came extremely close to overtaking UGA eSports Red in the rankings. With the normal season stats so close, the semifinal and final matches in the West are sure to be close as well. Rounding out the bottom of the bracket is the Drexel Dragoons Gold team, who tied UGA eSports Red during their first matchup of the normal season. Although the Dragoons are the underdogs in this semifinal matchup, they''ve shown that they have what it takes to take a game or two off of the frontrunners. The Western bracket can really be anyone''s to take, so be sure to stay tuned for playoff results.\r\n<h2>Eastern Conference</h2>\r\nOn the other side, the Eastern Conference playoff teams are (in order of playoff seed) UGA eSports: Black, UMBC Yellow, URI Royals 2.0, and USC B. Similar to the Western Conference, the top three teams in the East scored extremely close to each other during the regular season. With all three earning four wins a piece, both the Eastern semifinals and finals matches will be close ones. And like in the West, you can never count out the fourth seed, USC B. USC B will be facing the number one team in the East, UGA eSports: Black, and their last encounter ended in a tie. With both Conferences boasting incredibly close matchups, the teams will have to put in the extra effort to make it to the grand finals.\r\n<h2>Playoffs and Beyond</h2>\r\nIn the upcoming weeks, the teams will fight for the right to face their counterpart regional champion and win the Division Two championship title. As the matches play out and conference champions are crowned, be sure to check back <a href="http://www.ncespa.com/csgo/playoffs">here</a> to find updates.\r\n\r\nFor the League of Legends Division Two playoffs, the prize pool will have a total value of $450 in Riot Point cards, with first place taking home $250, second taking $100, and third and fourth taking $50 each. With half of the playoff teams earning a portion of the prize pool, the players will be in for some close matches!\r\n<h2>Division One Grand Championship</h2>\r\nIf you are keeping up with the Division Two playoff teams and championships, make sure you don''t miss out on the Division One Grand Championship as well. With the best teams in North America meeting on the Rift, stay tuned to the NCeSPA <a href="http://www.twitch.tv/ncespa">Twitch Channel</a> or grab tickets to the finals in Santa Ana, California for the big event on June 26th! The event will not only feature the finals for League of Legends and Counter-Strike: Global Offensive, but will also be a great place to meet fellow gamers, grab some free swag, and even witness our collegiate teams take on pro teams.', 'National Collegiate League of Legends League Season 2016 DII Regular Season Recap', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'ncll-2016-d2-regular-season-recap', '', '', '2016-09-20 22:41:41', '2016-09-21 02:41:41', '', 0, 'http://esport.dev/?p=8', 0, 'post', '', 0),
